			<h1><span class="less"><a href="index.html">SLE 2024</a> paper:</span><br><i>Trellis: A Domain-Specific Language for Hidden Markov Models with Sparse Transitions</i></h1>
			<h2><a href="../profile/LarsHummelgren.html">Lars Hummelgren</a>, <a href="../profile/ViktorPalmkvist.html">Viktor Palmkvist</a>, <a href="../profile/LinneaStjerna.html">Linnea Stjerna</a>, <a href="../profile/XuechunXu.html">Xuechun Xu</a>, <a href="../profile/JoakimJaldén.html">Joakim Jaldén</a>, <a href="../profile/DavidBroman.html">David Broman</a></h2>
<ul><li>DOI: <a href="https://doi.org/10.1145/3687997.3695641">10.1145/3687997.3695641</a></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t3c.html"><span class="tagM">T3C: DSLs</span></a><ul><li> Trellis is a DSL for specifying sparse HMMs at a high level while generating efficient implementations.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t4c.html"><span class="tagL">T4C: Vertical Transformation</span></a><ul><li> It relies on compilation/generation to GPU-accelerated code to achieve high performance.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t5f.html"><span class="tagL">T5F: Performance</span></a><ul><li> A key goal is performance for large sparse models via GPU acceleration and sparsity-aware execution.
</li></ul></li></ul>
